<h1
id="deriving-the-schrödinger-equation-from-sourcefree-maxwell-dynamics">Deriving
the Schrödinger Equation from Source‑Free Maxwell Dynamics</h1>
<p><em>A geometry‑based route from classical fields to quantum
mechanics</em></p>
<p>Anes Palma, An M. Rodriguez (<a
href="mailto:an@preferredframe.com">an@preferredframe.com</a>)</p>
<p>29 July 2025</p>
<h2 id="abstract">Abstract</h2>
<p>Maxwell equations in vacuum predict discrete energies when an
electromagnetic field forms a self‑confined toroidal standing pattern.
For any component <span
class="math inline"><em>F</em>(<strong>r</strong>, <em>t</em>)</span> of
the electromagnetic fields <span
class="math inline"><strong>E</strong>, <strong>B</strong></span>, we
isolate the forward‑time spectral part, keep all derivative terms
exactly, and obtain—within a rigorously bounded, bandwidth‑squared
remainder—the Schrödinger equation</p>
<p><span class="math display">$$
i\hbar\,\partial_t\psi=-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\nabla^{2}\psi,
\qquad
\hbar=\frac{E_{11}}{\omega_{11}},\;
m=\frac{E_{11}}{c^{2}}.
$$</span></p>
<p>Planck’s constant and the inertial mass thus emerge from the geometry
and energy of the fundamental toroidal mode. External influences appear
through local phase‑speed variations, yielding a potential term. Four
mathematically equivalent derivations confirm the result and quantify
finite‑bandwidth corrections. Apparent trajectory bending stems from
light slowing in regions of higher energy density, not from curved
space‑time.</p>
<h2 id="oneline-summary">One‑line summary</h2>
<p>Schrödinger’s equation, with <span
class="math inline">ℏ</span> and <span
class="math inline"><em>m</em></span>, arises directly from Maxwell
fields confined to a toroidal standing wave.</p>
<h2 id="keywords">Keywords</h2>
<p>classical electromagnetism; toroidal quantisation; analytic signal;
emergent quantum mechanics; Rydberg ladder; effective refractive
index</p>
<h2 id="introduction">1 Introduction</h2>
<p>Quantum mechanics is usually introduced axiomatically. Maxwell’s
equations, in contrast, were distilled from experiment—Coulomb’s law,
Faraday’s induction, Ampère–Ørsted magnetism, and Hertz’s verification
of electromagnetic waves. Uniting these experimentally grounded field
laws with quantum theory shows that the Schrödinger equation follows
from classical electromagnetism alone. In this framework mass is treated
as an electromagnetic object with field structure. Using the well‑known
relation relating energy and mass, <span
class="math inline"><em>E</em> = <em>m</em><em>c</em><sup>2</sup></span>,
an electromagnetic account of inertia naturally extends to the broader
principle that energy attracts energy—a theme developed in our earlier
work on emergent inverse‑square forces.</p>
<h2 id="maxwell-wave-equation">2 Maxwell Wave Equation</h2>
<p>For any Cartesian component <span
class="math inline"><em>F</em>(<strong>r</strong>, <em>t</em>)</span> of
<span class="math inline"><strong>E</strong></span> or <span
class="math inline"><strong>B</strong></span> in vacuum</p>
<p><span class="math display">$$
\left(\nabla^{2}-\frac{1}{c^{2}}\partial_t^{2}\right)F(\mathbf r,t)=0.
\tag{1}
$$</span></p>
<h2 id="toroidal-standing-modes">3 Toroidal Standing Modes</h2>
<p>Let the major and minor radii be <span
class="math inline"><em>R</em></span> and <span
class="math inline"><em>r</em></span>. Integer windings <span
class="math inline">(<em>n</em><sub>1</sub>, <em>n</em><sub>2</sub>)</span>
impose</p>
<p><span class="math display">$$
k_1=\frac{n_1}{R},\qquad
k_2=\frac{n_2}{r},\qquad
k^{2}=k_1^{2}+k_2^{2},\qquad
\omega_{n_1n_2}=ck .
$$</span></p>
<p>The energy of a mode is</p>
<p><span class="math display">$$
E_{n_1n_2}=\hbar_g\,\omega_{n_1n_2},\qquad
\hbar_g=\frac{E_{11}}{\omega_{11}}, \tag{2}
$$</span></p>
<p>producing the ladder <span
class="math inline"><em>E</em><sub><em>n</em></sub> = <em>E</em><sub>11</sub>/<em>n</em><sup>2</sup></span>
for symmetric windings <span
class="math inline"><em>n</em><sub>1</sub> = <em>n</em><sub>2</sub> = <em>n</em></span>.</p>
<h2 id="exact-derivation-via-analytic-signal">4 Exact Derivation via
Analytic Signal</h2>
<h3 id="forwardtime-spectral-projection">4.1 Forward‑time spectral
projection</h3>
<p>Define the analytic (positive‑time) signal</p>
<p><span
class="math display"><em>F</em><sup>(+)</sup>(<strong>r</strong>, <em>t</em>) = ∫<sub>0</sub><sup>∞</sup><em>F̃</em>(<strong>r</strong>, <em>ω</em>) <em>e</em><sup>−<em>i</em><em>ω</em><em>t</em></sup> <em>d</em><em>ω</em>,</span></p>
<p>which also satisfies (1). Extract the carrier at <span
class="math inline"><em>ω</em><sub>11</sub></span>:</p>
<p><span
class="math display"><em>ψ</em>(<strong>r</strong>, <em>t</em>) = <em>e</em><sup><em>i</em><em>ω</em><sub>11</sub><em>t</em></sup> <em>F</em><sup>(+)</sup>(<strong>r</strong>, <em>t</em>).</span></p>
<h3 id="substitution-and-exact-algebra">4.2 Substitution and exact
algebra</h3>
<p>Insert the derivatives of <span class="math inline"><em>ψ</em></span>
into (1) and divide by <span
class="math inline"><em>e</em><sup>−<em>i</em><em>ω</em><sub>11</sub><em>t</em></sup></span>:</p>
<p><span class="math display">$$
\nabla^{2}\psi-\frac{1}{c^{2}}\partial_t^{2}\psi
+\frac{2i\omega_{11}}{c^{2}}\partial_t\psi
+\frac{\omega_{11}^{2}}{c^{2}}\psi=0. \tag{4}
$$</span></p>
<p>Because <span
class="math inline"><em>ω</em><sub>11</sub> = <em>c</em><em>k</em><sub>11</sub></span>,
adding and subtracting <span
class="math inline"><em>k</em><sub>11</sub><sup>2</sup><em>ψ</em></span>
cancels the last term, leaving an exact equation with a first‑order time
derivative.</p>
<h3 id="bandwidth-control">4.3 Bandwidth control</h3>
<p>Rearrange (4):</p>
<p><span class="math display">$$
i\partial_t\psi=-\frac{c^{2}}{2\omega_{11}}\nabla^{2}\psi
+\frac{1}{2\omega_{11}c^{2}}\partial_t^{2}\psi. \tag{5}
$$</span></p>
<p>For root‑mean‑square spectral width <span
class="math inline"><em>Δ</em><em>ω</em></span>, the remainder obeys</p>
<p><span class="math display">$$
\left\|\frac{1}{2\omega_{11}c^{2}}\partial_t^{2}\psi\right\|
\le\frac{\Delta\omega^{2}}{2\omega_{11}c^{2}}\|\psi\|
=O(\epsilon^{2}),\qquad
\epsilon=\frac{\Delta\omega}{\omega_{11}}\ll1. \tag{6}
$$</span></p>
<h3 id="emergent-hbar-and-m">4.4 Emergent <span
class="math inline">ℏ</span> and <span
class="math inline"><em>m</em></span></h3>
<p>Identify</p>
<p><span class="math display">$$
\hbar=\frac{E_{11}}{\omega_{11}},\qquad
m=\frac{E_{11}}{c^{2}}, \tag{7}
$$</span></p>
<p>so <span
class="math inline"><em>c</em><sup>2</sup>/(2<em>ω</em><sub>11</sub>) = ℏ/(2<em>m</em>)</span>.
Discarding the <span
class="math inline"><em>O</em>(<em>ϵ</em><sup>2</sup>)</span> term
yields</p>
<p><span class="math display">$$
i\hbar\,\partial_t\psi=-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\nabla^{2}\psi+O(\epsilon^{2}).
\tag{8}
$$</span></p>
<h2 id="external-influences-without-curvature">5 External Influences
Without Curvature</h2>
<p>A slow phase‑speed variation <span
class="math inline"><em>c</em> → <em>c</em><sub>eff</sub>(<strong>r</strong>) = <em>c</em>/<em>n</em>(<strong>r</strong>)</span>
shifts the carrier frequency:</p>
<p><span class="math display">$$
\omega_{11}\to\omega_{11}+\frac{V(\mathbf r)}{\hbar},\qquad
V(\mathbf r)=E_{11}\bigl[n(\mathbf r)-1\bigr]. \tag{9}
$$</span></p>
<p>Repeating the algebra gives</p>
<p><span class="math display">$$
i\hbar\,\partial_t\psi=\Bigl[-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\nabla^{2}+V(\mathbf
r)\Bigr]\psi+O(\epsilon^{2}). \tag{10}
$$</span></p>
<p>Apparent trajectory bending is thus a dielectric‑style slowing of
light, not space‑time curvature.</p>
